         <h1>James Stern, 88, a Prolific Writer Of Short Stories and a Translator </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>James Stern , an Anglo-Irish critic and prolific writer of short stories that traced his wanderings through the British Isles , Africa , the Pacific and America , died on Monday at his home in Tisbury , England . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 88 . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Stern was in frail health after he broke a hip several months ago , said a friend , the writer Nora Sayre . <br><blue>4</blue>He was the author of more than 50 short stories , a translator of many German writers and the writer of a widely read study of Europe after World War II . <br><blue>5</blue>Mr. Stern lived in New York for two decades , starting in 1939 . <br><blue>6</blue>While here he contributed to The New Republic , Harper 's Magazine and The Nation , and worked briefly for Time magazine . <br><blue>7</blue>Over the years he contributed scores of reviews to The New York Times Book Review . <br><blue>8</blue>Told of Wartime Suffering In " The Hidden Damage , " published in 1947 , Mr. Stern related the spiritual havoc suffered by Western Europeans in World War II , as well as his own reminiscences of a childhood in Ireland and England . <br><blue>9</blue>Mr. Stern was sent to Europe by the War Department in 1945 as a member of the Strategic Bombing Survey to discover the effects of bombing on the German public . <br><blue>10</blue>" The Hidden Damage " was his own version of the chaos he saw and felt . <br><blue>11</blue>His works also included " The Heartless Land " ( 1932 ) , dealing with life in Rhodesia ; " Something Wrong " ( 1938 ) , about parents and children ; " The Man Who Was Loved " ( 1951 ) , a collection of short stories , and another collection , " The Stories of James Stern , " published in 1969 . ' <br><blue>12</blue>A Traveling Writer ' The critic V. S. Pritchett said of Mr. Stern 's writing style : " He is essentially a traveling writer , visiting people 's lives , making thoughtful and humane observations about them , passionate in his rendering of landscape , capable of many kinds of story , strong in episode and situation . " <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Stern turned to short-story writing in 1930 as a means of escaping from the boredom of working as a bank clerk in London . <br><blue>14</blue>He had attended Eton and Sandhurst , and then for a time worked as a steeplechase rider , pig farmer and cattle rancher . <br><blue>15</blue>He was the translator , sometimes in collaboration with his wife , Tania Stern , of many writers in German , including Thomas Mann , Franz Kafka and Erich Maria Remarque . <br><blue>16</blue>He is survived by his wife and a brother , Peter Stern . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>World War II</m_str> (4_29) 	<m_str>World War II</m_str> (8_27) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>them</m_str> (12_37) 	<m_str>people 's</m_str> (12_27) 	<br><blue>3(26)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_10) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern</m_str> (8_16) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern 's</m_str> (12_12) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>Peter Stern</m_str> (16_11) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (12_19) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_15) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_3) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_34) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_7) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_33) 	<m_str>Mr. Stern</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_41) 	<m_str>James Stern</m_str> (11_58) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_13) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (3_8) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_4) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (11_1) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
